        { text: "Write a 4-line verse using near-rhymes instead of perfect rhymes. Lines 1 and 3 rhyme loosely. Lines 2 and 4 rhyme loosely. Read it aloud — feel how near-rhymes create a soft echo in the mouth rather than a hard click.", why: "ABAB near-rhyme is the most common lyric pattern. It creates structure without forcing word choices that sound cliched." },
        { text: "Try internal rhyme: rhyming within a line, not just at the end. 'The salt and the sand on my hands.' Feel how the repeated 'a' vowel binds the line physically — the mouth keeps returning to the same shape, and the chest resonates with the pattern.", why: "Internal rhyme adds musicality without the rigidity of end-rhyme. It makes lines feel crafted and flowing." },
        { text: "Sing your rhymed and near-rhymed verses over a chord progression. Notice how rhyme affects the body's phrasing — rhymed words naturally land on strong beats, and the mouth anticipates the familiar vowel shape before it arrives.", why: "Rhyme and rhythm are deeply connected. Placing rhymed syllables on stressed beats reinforces both the musical and lyrical pattern." }
