      steps: [
        { text: "Speak a lyric line aloud: 'The WAVES are ROLL-ing IN to-DAY.' Feel how your body naturally emphasizes certain syllables — the chest pushes air on WAVES, ROLL, IN. The capitalized syllables are where your body wants to land. Mark them.", why: "English has natural stress patterns. Every word has stressed and unstressed syllables. Ignoring them makes lyrics sound wrong." },
        { text: "Now sing the line over your chord progression. Hear each stressed syllable arriving in the body before you sing it — WAVES wants to land in the chest on a strong beat, ROLL wants the mask. Do the stressed syllables land on strong beats (1 and 3) and high notes? When stress, beat, and body location all converge, the prosody is right.", why: "When stress and beat align, lyrics sound effortless. When they clash, the listener feels something's 'off' even if they can't say why." },
        { text: "Find a line in your lyrics where the prosody is wrong — where an unstressed syllable lands on a strong beat. Sing it and feel the physical mismatch: the body wants to emphasize one syllable, but the melody forces another. The discomfort is real and physical. Rewrite the melody or the words to fix it.", why: "Prosody fixes are the single most impactful edit you can make. A song with good prosody sounds professional even if the melody is simple." },
        { text: "Speak-sing test: speak the lyrics naturally, then sing them. If the melody follows your speech rhythm — if the body produces both in the same motion — the prosody is perfect. The words and melody feel like one breath.", why: "The speak-sing test is the fastest prosody check. If the melody contradicts your natural speech, something needs to change." }
      ],
      feel: "Good prosody feels invisible — the words and melody seem like they were born together because the body produces them as one act. The stressed syllable, the melodic accent, and the body's emphasis all land simultaneously. Bad prosody feels like wearing shoes on the wrong feet: the body wants to stress one syllable but the melody forces another, and that physical mismatch is what makes it sound wrong.",
      wrong: "If you're stressed the wrong way, sometimes flipping two words fixes it: 'today the waves' -> 'the waves today.' Small word-order changes can fix prosody without changing meaning.",
